celebrations in grand scale with the Co-host & support of American Telangana Society(ATS). The association celebrated Bathukamma/Jammi Pooja/Dusshera celebrations with more than 600-plus guests on Oct 10th 2021 at Panchavati, SVS Balaji Temple Aurora, IL. About 100 women from Bathukamma team purchased and wore matching Kanchi pattu sarees and brought color and uniqueness to set a record among all other Bathukamma celebrations across the world. This initiative was done to support impoverished weavers in South India and help them financially. TAGC Bathukamma chair Archana Podduturi and TAGC President Venkat Gunuganti welcomed all the guests with a brief introduction about the significance of the festival. Delicious vegetarian lunch was offered to all the guests coordinated by Food Chair Vijay Beeram. TAGC raised funds to support Vaidehi Seva Samithi orphanage for destitute girls and women coordinated by Co-chairs Ramya and Rajitha. More than 100 Women had donated funds and participated in this good cause. Well renowned folk singer Niharika renditioned beautiful songs which further energized the passion of women playing Bathukamma. One of the highlighted programs is a special Kolatam by 60+ ladies in a coordinated fashion. After Bathukamma immersion, all the families participated in Shammi/Jammi puja conducted by Balaji temple priest Sri Hanumantha Prasad garu on the occasion of Dusshera. ATS Leadership team along with long time sponsors Ashok Lakshmanan PMSI, Krishna Rangaraju NYLife, presented the gifts to Bathukamma competition winners and Raffle winners. Celebrations were a grand success with the support of BOD’s and long time volunteers. Culture and traditions were followed in every aspect of these celebrations. Zari work is basically the weaving of thin wires of gold, silver and copper to create beautiful patterns and motifs into the fabric, while brocade is the inter weaving of silk, gold and silver threads to create a unique, intricate fabric used both in designing as well as appliqué techniques. Other works used on Banarasi Sarees are minakari (mina work), gold work, and jaal work (net work). Sometimes, pita work, kundan work, cut work, and appliqué is also used on these Sarees.\n\nDesigner Banarasi sarees are made in a variety of colours and are embellished with characteristic motifs and designs on the pallu and the body of the Saree. Many of these motifs are traditional and have been used since the Mughal age, when the weaving industry was initially prospering and growing at its peak, including bel, buti, paisley motifs, peacocks, jhalar etc. These designs are a beautiful blend of the Indian culture with Mughal influences and mores. Modern Banarasi Sarees have gone on to include a myriad of patterns and motifs that are fresh and creative. Banarasi Saree borders are usually broad and decorated with these craft techniques making them look royal and full of grace. Golden Banaras Saree borders in zari work and jhalar are particularly very popular.\n#diwalishopping #banarsisaari #katansilksaree #pureelegance #sixyards #silklovers #Colorsofredmondexclusivesaari 00:54:27","updated":"2021-11-05 01:40:54","type":"photo","description":"IE US News: Biden Nominates Indian American for a Key Position in Air Force \n\nPresident Biden announced his plans to nominate Indian American Ravi Chaudhary, a former Federal Aviation Administration official, for a key position at Pentagon. Biden’s intent to appoint him as the Air Force’s next assistant secretary for installations, environment and energy reaffirms that the Indian American community is integral to the growth of the United States. Ravi Chaudhary who served the Department of Transportation, Air Force, and Space Force for over 20 years will be given a massive portfolio if approved by the Senate. \n\nA graduate in aeronautical engineering from the US Air Force Academy, Chaudhary worked on space launch operations and flight safety activities for the full operational capability of the GPS constellation. He also supported NASA’s International Space Station programs ensuring the safety of NASA astronauts in the early years of his career. As a flight test engineer, he was responsible for flight certification of military avionics and hardware for Air Force modernization programs supporting flight safety and mishap prevention. As a C-17 pilot, he conducted global flight operations, including several combat missions in Afghanistan and Iraq. He studied MA in Operational Arts and Military Science from the US Air University. \n\nHe also served as Director of Advanced Programs and Innovation at the US Department of Transportation where he was responsible for the execution of advanced development and research programs in support of the Federal Aviation Administration (FAA)’s Commercial Space Transportation mission. He was also responsible for the integration and support of aviation operations in nine regions across the country. \n\nA Doctorate in Executive Leadership and Innovation from Georgetown University, he also served as a member of former President Obama’s Advisory Commission on Asian Americans and Pacific Islanders (AAPI). He documented instances of racism against the AAPI members and advised the Obama administration on executive efforts to improve support for the APPI community.","message":"President Biden announced his plans to nominate Indian American Ravi Chaudhary, a former Federal Aviation Administration official, for a key position at Pentagon. Biden’s intent to appoint him as the Air Force’s next assistant secretary for installations, environment and energy reaffirms that the Indian American community is integral to the growth of the United States. Ravi Chaudhary who served the Department of Transportation, Air Force, and Space Force for over 20 years will be given a massive portfolio if approved by the Senate. A graduate in aeronautical engineering from the US Air Force Academy, Chaudhary worked on space launch operations and flight safety activities for the full operational capability of the GPS constellation. He also supported NASA’s International Space Station programs ensuring the safety of NASA astronauts in the early years of his career. As a flight test engineer, he was responsible for flight certification of military avionics and hardware for Air Force modernization programs supporting flight safety and mishap prevention. As a C-17 pilot, he conducted global flight operations, including several combat missions in Afghanistan and Iraq. He studied MA in Operational Arts and Military Science from the US Air University. He also served as Director of Advanced Programs and Innovation at the US Department of Transportation where he was responsible for the execution of advanced development and research programs in support of the Federal Aviation Administration (FAA)’s Commercial Space Transportation mission. He was also responsible for the integration and support of aviation operations in nine regions across the country. A Doctorate in Executive Leadership and Innovation from Georgetown University, he also served as a member of former President Obama’s Advisory Commission on Asian Americans and Pacific Islanders (AAPI). He documented instances of racism against the AAPI members and advised the Obama administration on executive efforts to improve support for the APPI
